Tuesday

Goals:

  • Center, Shape, and Spread for Quantitative Variables
  • Outliers, boxplots

Measures of center: tell whats normal.

Definition: a measure is robust if its not strongly affected by outliers/skew.

Example: median is robust (not affected by outliers), but mean is NOT robust. Example: 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 19.

Shape of a distribution

Common shapes:

  • Symmetric. Evenly distributed on either side of the middle.
  • Left skew (left tail)
  • Right skew (right tail)

Exercise: What shape?

Based on the following, what shape does the variable have and how do the mean and median compare?

  1. Variable: Exam scores in a large class for an easy exam. Shape: left skew, most students scored well, only a few scored poorly. Wed expect the mean score to lower than the median.

  2. Variable: salaries in a large corporation. Strong right skew! Most employees earn a normal amount, a select few earn much more. Ex: In 2018, revealed that the CEO of Activision earned 300x the average salary! The mean salary will be a lot larger, could skew our perception of wealth in the corporation.

  3. Variable: height of adult men in the US. Symmetric dist! Most people have average height, only a few are exceptionally tall or short. Wed expect that the mean and median are similar.

  4. Variable: heights of all adults in the US, men and women. Shape: bimodal. Still fairly symmetric, since 50/50 gender.

Measures of Spread (quantitative variable)

I.e., how much variability? How far away do we expect observations to be from the center?

Three big measures:

  1. Range: max - min

Example: range of sepal lengths:

summary(iris$Sepal.Length)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   4.300   5.100   5.800   5.843   6.400   7.900

Range: 3.6cm. Advantage: easy! Big disadvantage: super, duper, extra not robust!!! Even one outlier wrecks the range.

  1. Standard deviation. The deviation for an observation is just its distance from the mean: x - xbar. For std deviation, we find all deviations for all observations, and (roughly) take their average. Std dev = average distance from the center.

Formula:

\[s=\sqrt{\sum\frac{(x-\bar{x})^2}{n-1}}\]

  1. Interquartile Range = The distance between the quartiles Q1 and Q3. Note: Q1 is the median of the lower half. Q3 is the median of the upper half). IQR gives us the range/spread of the middle 50% of the data.

Interesting note: all three of these are totally different approaches, but theyre all reasonable ways to measure spread.

Q: Which of the three measures of spread is robust?
A: Only the IQR, since its determined by the middle stuff. Outliers have no effect.

Outliers

Outliers are unusual measurements! Couple of different methods for determining. Heres ours:

Well define an outlier to be any measurement thats more than 1.5 IQRs away from Q1 or Q3.

Low cutoff: \[Q1 - 1.5\cdot IQR\]

high cutoff: \[Q3 + 1.5\cdot IQR\]

Example Verify that 20 is an outlier in 1,2,3,4,5,20.

Boxplots

Boxplots visualize the IQR. Super useful for comparing multiple quant. variables, since its easy to have multiple boxplots on the same axes.

Example: Iris dataset

boxplot(iris$Sepal.Length)

Comparing all variables:

boxplot(iris)

Comparing by species:

boxplot(data=iris, Sepal.Length~Species)

Weird plots

Weve seen some typical plots. Example, iris data:

boxplot(data=iris, Sepal.Length~Species)

Observations: Q1 for versicolor about 5.7ish.

Q: which species has the highest center? Virginica!

Q: which species has the smallest spread? Setosa sepal lengths have least variability.

Q: Outliers? Looks like virginica has one low outlier.

Weird example: Cirp Survey Data

Take a look:

cirpData <- read.csv("CIRP_DATA_2014_CLEAN.csv")
head(cirpData)

Note: totally need metadata.

Q: what about english? How much english have DU students had?

boxplot(cirpData$YRSTUDY1)

Analysis: almost everyone responded 6, i.e., the vast majority of incoming DU students took 4 years of english in HS. Q1 = M = Q3 = 6.

Another weird example: scatterplot

Q: Is there a relationship between RATE01 (academic ability) and RATE03 (competitiveness).

qplot(cirpData$RATE01, cirpData$RATE03)

Woah! weird! Whats going on? Discrete data often doesnt work well with scatterplots. Cant tell how many points!

Neat trick: jitter. Jittering means adding a small amount of random noise.

qplot(cirpData$RATE01, cirpData$RATE03)+geom_jitter()

Ah! Now we can see a roughly positive pattern.

Moral of the story: think carefully about any visualition you do. Whats it mean?

qplot(iris$Sepal.Length, iris$Sepal.Width)

Example: Exam scores

66, 67, 71, 71, 74, 76, 76, 78, 80, 99

Check for outliers, make a boxplot, describe shape.

IQR: 7, Q1 = 71, Q3 = 78

Low cutoff:

71 - 1.5*7
## [1] 60.5

High cutoff:

78+1.5*7
## [1] 88.5

Note: 99 is an outlier!

Warning for boxplot: draw axis first!

Shape: aside from outlier, theres a little left skew.

boxplot(c(66, 67, 71, 71, 74, 76, 76, 78, 80, 99), horizontal = TRUE)

boxplot(iris)

Empirical Rule and Z scores

We know about outliers, but what about everything else? Common question: how unusual is a measurement in our data?

Major tool: z scores (standard scores).

Z scores measure the distance from a point to the mean, in units of standard deviation! I.e., how many standard deviations above or below the mean are you?

Example: Adult women in the US have mean height 64" with std dev 2.4" (true). Prof miller 75". Compute her z score!

(75-64)/2.4
## [1] 4.583333

Note about rounding: three decimals is enough.

Why is this useful? It lets us compare elements of different datasets! It accounts for the center and spread of the respective distributions.

Example: Exam scores. On ACT, the mean score for test takers is 24, std dev 3. On SAT, the mean score is 680, with std dev 40.

If Alex got a 28 on the ACT, and Beth got 720 on the SAT, who scored better?

Z scores!

Alex:

(28- 24)/3
## [1] 1.333333

Beth:

(720-680)/40
## [1] 1

boxplot(iris)

boxplot(data=iris, Sepal.Length~Species)

Q: whats Q1 for versicolor? A: 5.6ish.

Q: of the three species, which has the highest center? The typical Sepal Length for virginica is the greatest!

Q: Which of the three has the smallest spread? A: setosa has less variability.

Example: English in CIRP DATA

boxplot(cirpData$YRSTUDY1)

Relationships between variables

Q: Is there a relationship between RATE01 (academic ability) and RATE03 (competitiveness). Look at scatterplot.

qplot(data=cirpData, x=RATE01, y=RATE03)

Woah! Whats going on? Discrete data: cant tell how many students are in each category!

Neat trick: jitter. Jitter is a small amount of random noise added to data.

qplot(data=cirpData, x=RATE01, y=RATE03)+geom_jitter()

Jitter helps us see density for discrete variables.

Moral of the story: sometimes visualizations are weird/unexpected. Think carefully about what theyre telling you.

boxplot(iris)

How unusual is our data? Z-scores

For an observation (x), the z-score is the number of standard deviations above (or below) the mean. I.e., it tells how far x is from the mean, in units of standard deviations.

Z scores are useful for comparing different data sets.

Example: Exam scores. On the ACT, the average score is 24 with std dev 3. On the the SAT, the average score is 680 with std dev 40.

If Alex scores 28 on the ACT, and Beth scores 720 on the SAT, who scored better?

A: compute z scores!

For Alex:

(28-24)/3
## [1] 1.333333

Beth:

(720-680)/40
## [1] 1
